06332nam a22012615i 9780691199986DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a9780691199986  a(DE-B1597)573234  a(OCoLC)1232280251  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHJ2250 7aBUS0640002bisacsh04a336.2009223  aQL 400qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/141714:1 aKeen, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRebellion, Rascals, and Revenue :bTax Follies and Wisdom through the Ages /cJoel Slemrod, Michael Keen. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (536 p.) :b59 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tRebellion, Rascals, and Revenue -- tPart I. Plunder and power -- tPart II. Winners and Losers -- tPart III. Changing Our Ways -- tPart IV. Taxes Don’t Collect Themselves -- tPart V. Making Taxes -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA gripping account of taxation told through lively, dramatic, and sometimes ludicrous stories drawn from around the world and across the ages Governments have always struggled to tax in ways that are effective and tolerably fair. Sometimes they fail grotesquely, as when, in 1898, the British ignited a rebellion in Sierra Leone by imposing a tax on huts—and, in repressing it, ended up burning the very huts they intended to tax. Sometimes they succeed astonishingly, as when, in eighteenth-century Britain, a cut in the tax on tea massively increased revenue. In this entertaining book, two leading authorities on taxation, Michael Keen and Joel Slemrod, provide a fascinating and informative tour through these and many other episodes in tax history, both preposterous and dramatic—from the plundering described by Herodotus and an Incan tax payable in lice to the (misremembered) Boston Tea Party and the scandals of the Panama Papers. Along the way, readers meet a colorful cast of tax rascals, and even a few tax heroes.While it is hard to fathom the inspiration behind such taxes as one on ships that tended to make them sink, Keen and Slemrod show that yesterday’s tax systems have more in common with ours than we may think. Georgian England’s window tax now seems quaint, but was an ingenious way of judging wealth unobtrusively. And Tsar Peter the Great’s tax on beards aimed to induce the nobility to shave, much like today’s carbon taxes aim to slow global warming.Rebellions, Rascals, and Revenue is a surprising and one-of-a-kind account of how history illuminates the perennial challenges and timeless principles of taxation—and how the past holds clues to solving the tax problems of today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aTaxationxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Taxation / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aChina.  aEnglish.  aFrance.  aGreat Britain.  aHut Tax War.  aJapan.  aMaori.  aNew Zealand.  aUnited States.  aVAT.  aVlad the Impaler.  aancient taxes.  aanecdotes.  abizarre.  acheating.  adeath and taxes.  adeduction.  adog tax.  adumbest taxes.  aevasion.  aexemption.  afailed.  ahaven.  ahistory of taxation.  amodern taxes.  aorigin of income tax.  apoll.  aprotests.  arevenue.  asales.  asmartest taxes.  astamp.  astrangest taxes.  asuccessful.  atariffs.  atax revolts.  atax.  ause.  aweird.1 aSlemrod, Joel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2021 Englishz978311075404908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru